{"title_page": "Giovanni Battista Rizza", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2011}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Giovanni Battista Rizza\n| image             = <!--(filename only)-->\n| image_size        =\n| alt               =\n| caption           =\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1924|2|7|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Piazza Armerina]]\n| death_date        = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|1924|2|7|df=y}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place       =\n| residence         = [[Parma]]\n| citizenship       =\n| nationality       = Italian\n| fields            = {{plainlist|\n*[[Hypercomplex analysis]]\n*[[Several complex variables]]\n*[[Differential geometry]]}}\n| workplaces        = {{plainlist|\n*[[Universit\u00e0 degli Studi di Genova]]\n*[[Istituto Nazionale di Alta Matematica]]\n*[[Sapienza University of Rome]]\n*[[Universit\u00e0 degli Studi di Parma]]}}\n| alma_mater        = [[Universit\u00e0 degli Studi di Genova]]\n| doctoral_advisor  = [[Enzo Martinelli]]\n| academic_advisors =\n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students  =\n| known_for         = {{plainlist|\n*Integral representation of [[pluriharmonic function]]s\n*[[Rizza manifold]]s\n*[[Hypercomplex analysis|Theory of functions on Algebras]]}}\n| influences        =\n| influenced        =\n| awards            = {{plainlist|\n*[[Premio Ottorino Pomini]] of the [[Unione Matematica Italiana]] (1954),<ref name=\"Pomini\">The detailed motivation for the award is reported in the {{harvnb|Bollettino UMI|1954|pp=477\u2013478}}. The high scientific value of the works of the two young [[mathematician]]s induced the commission to ask the [[Benefactor (law)|benefactor]]s supporting the prize for a double award: their request was accepted.</ref>\n*[[Golden medal]] \"[[Benemeriti della Scuola, della Cultura, dell'Arte]]\" (awarded by the [[President of the Italian Republic]]) (1973)<ref name=\"Ben\">See the [[#{{Harvid|Presidenza della Repubblica Italiana|1973}}|list of the recipients of the medal]].</ref>}}\n| signature         = <!--(filename only)-->\n| signature_alt     =\n| website           = \n| footnotes         =\n| spouse            = [[Lucilla Bassotti]]\n}}\n\n'''Giovanni Battista Rizza''' (born 7 February 1924) (at the [[registry office]] '''Giambattista Rizza''')<ref>See the [[#{{Harvid|Presidenza della Repubblica Italiana|1973}}|list of the recipients of the medal \"''Benemeriti della Scuola, della Cultura, dell'Arte''\"]] and the [[#{{Harvid|Il Ministro dell'Universit\u00e0 e della Ricerca Scientifica e Tecnologica|1999}}|Decreto ministeriale 17 febbraio 1999]] conferring him the title of \"[[Professor Emeritus]]\".</ref> is an Italian [[mathematician]], working in the fields of [[Several complex variables|complex analysis of several variables]] and in [[differential geometry]]: he is known for his contribution to hypercomplex analysis, notably for extending [[Cauchy's integral theorem]] and [[Cauchy's integral formula]] to complex functions of a [[hypercomplex number|hypercomplex variable]],<ref name=\"Pomini_motivation\">According to the motivation for the award of the \"''[[Premio Ottorino Pomini]]''\", reported on the {{harvtxt|Bollettino UMI|1954|p=477}}, \"Sono particolarmente degni di nota i risultati sui teoremi integrali per le funzioni regolari, sulle estensioni della formula integrale di Cauchy alle funzioni monogene sulle algebre complesse dotate di modulo commutative e sul conseguente sviluppo della relativa teoria, ed infine sulla struttura delle algebre di Clifford\" (\"Particularly notable results are the ones on the integral theorems for regular functions, the ones on the extension of Cauchy integral formula to complex commutative algebras with modulus, and lastly the ones on the structure of [[Clifford algebras]]\").</ref> the theory of [[pluriharmonic function]]s and for the introduction of the now called [[Rizza manifold]]s.\n\n==Biography==\n\n[[Image:1965 International Algebraic Geometry Symposium.jpg|thumb|350px|left|The International Symposium on Algebraic Geometry held in Rome in 1965. [[Enrico Bompiani]] talking to Giovanni Battista Rizza and [[Vittorio Dalla Volta]].]]\n\n===Life and academic career===\n\nBorn in [[Piazza Armerina]], the son of Giovanni and Angioletta Bocciarelli, he graduated from the [[Universit\u00e0 degli Studi di Genova]], earning his [[laurea]] degree in 1949 under the direction of [[Enzo Martinelli]].<ref name=\"mar1\">According to {{harvtxt|Martinelli|1994|p=1}}, he was his first [[doctoral student]].</ref> In 1956 he was in [[Rome]] at the [[INdAM]], having been awarded a scholarship for his early research activities.<ref>He, [[Giuseppe Arcidiacono]] and Dario Del Pasqua, were awarded the scholarship without sustaining the \"''colloquio''\"  (\"colloquium\" in English translation), an oral exam where the candidate was asked to answer questions posed by a scientific jury, according to {{harvtxt|Roghi|2005|p=46}} who reports also an excerpt of the motivation given by the commission for the awarding of the scholarship to Rizza: \"... perch\u00e9 trattasi di giovani di cui \u00e8 nota l'attivit\u00e0 scientifica...\", i.e. (English translation): \"...because they are young researchers whose scientific activity is known, ...\").</ref><ref>{{harvtxt|Roghi|2005|pp=8,29,277}} also states that the scientific commission of the institute in charge in 1956 was still the first one, formed on 23 November 1939: its members were [[Francesco Severi]] (the president), [[Luigi Fantappie]], [[Giulio Krall]], [[Enrico Bompiani]] and [[Mauro Picone]].</ref> A year later, in 1957, he was elected \"''discepolo ricercatore''\"<ref>\"Disciple researcher\" (English translation) was the appellation of junior research scientists working at the [[INdAM]]. See {{harv|Roghi|2005}} for further details.</ref> in the same institute.<ref name=\"GRp50\">See {{harv|Roghi|2005|p=50}}.</ref> During the same year,<ref>See {{harv|Roghi|2005|p=50}} and {{harvtxt|Severi|1958|p=III}}</ref> he gave some lectures on topics belonging to the field of [[several complex variables]],<ref>See {{harv|Rizza|1958}}.</ref> later included in the lecture notes {{harv|Severi|1958}}.<ref>{{harvtxt|Roghi|2005|p=50}} also precisely reports the costs carried by the [[INdAM]] to fund this course.</ref> In Rome he also met [[Lucilla Bassotti]], who eventually become his wife. In 1961, he won the competitive examination for the chair of \"Geometria analitica con elementi di Geometria Proiettiva e Geometria Descrittiva con Disegno\" of the [[University of Parma]],<ref>\"[[Analytic geometry]] with elements of [[projective geometry]] and [[descriptive geometry]] with [[drawing]]\" (English translation).</ref> scoring first out of the three finalists:<ref>See the announce on the {{harvtxt|Bollettino UMI|1962|p=454}}.</ref> a year later, in 1962, he became [[extraordinary professor]],<ref>See {{harv|Venturini|1963|p=15}}.</ref> and then, in 1965, [[ordinary professor]] to the same chair.<ref>See the [[#{{harvid|The Editorial Board|1965}}|1965 Yearbook of the University of Parma, p. 207]]: the exact date of this career advancement is 16th January 1965.</ref> In 1979 he became ordinary professor of \"''Geometria superiore''\",<ref>Literally \"higher geometry\": it is an Italian university course on advanced geometry topics.</ref> holding that chair uninterruptedly until 1994:<ref>See the [[#{{harvid|The Editorial Board|1980}}|1980 Yearbook of the University of Parma, p. 209]].</ref> from 1994 up to his retirement in 1997, he was \"''professore fuori ruolo''\" in the same department of mathematics where he worked for more than 35 years.<ref>See the [[#{{harvid|The Editorial Board|1995}}|1995 Yearbook of the University of Parma, pp. 887 and 1036]]: the locution, literally meaning \"out of role professor\", identifies a nearly retired professor which is not in charge of any particular university course.</ref>\n\nApart from his research and teaching work, he was actively involved as a member of the editorial board of the \"''[[Rivista di Matematica della Universit\u00e0 di Parma]]''\", and served also as the journal director from 1992 to 1997.<ref>According to the [[timeline]] of Editors in Chief of the \"''Rivista''\", as reported in the [[#{{harvid|Rivista di Matematica della Universit\u00e0 di Parma|2013}}|historical section of the journal web site]].</ref>\n\n===Honors===\n\nIn 1954 he was awarded the [[Ottorino Pomini prize]] by the [[Unione Matematica Italiana]], jointly with [[Gabriele Darbo]]: the judging commission was composed by [[Giovanni Sansone]] (as the president), [[Alessandro Terracini]], [[Beniamino Segre]], [[Giuseppe Scorza-Dragoni]], [[Carlo Miranda]], [[Mario Villa]] and [[Enzo Martinelli]] (as the secretary).<ref name=\"Pomini\"/>\n\nIn 1973 he was awarded the [[golden medal]] \"[[Benemeriti della Scuola, della Cultura, dell'Arte]]\" by the [[President of the Italian Republic]],<ref name=\"Ben\"/> as an acknowledgement his research and teaching and achievements as civil servant at the University of Parma.<ref>See {{harv|Schreiber|1973|p=1}}.</ref>\n\nIn 1995, to celebrate his 70th birthday, an international conference on differential geometry was organized in Parma: the [[proceedings]] were later published as a special issue of the \"Rivista di Matematica della Universit\u00e0 di Parma\".<ref>See {{harv|Donnini|Gigante|Mangione|1994}}. In the [[preface]], the editors and members of the organizing committee briefly commemorate [[Franco Tricerri]], former pupil of Rizza and speaker at the conference, who died in a [[plane crash]] in [[China]] few weeks before the proceedings of the conference were published (<!-- ''[[ibid.]]'', -->[[#{{harvid|Donnini|Gigante|Mangione|1994}}|p. iii]]).</ref>\nIn 1999 the University of Parma, where he worked for more than 35 years, awarded him the title of [[professor emeritus]].<ref>According to [[#{{Harvid|Il Ministro dell'Universit\u00e0 e della Ricerca Scientifica e Tecnologica|1999}}|Decreto ministeriale 17 febbraio 1999]].</ref>\n\nHe is currently an honorary member of the [[Balkan Society of Geometers]] and life member of the [[Tensor Society]].<ref>See the list of members of the {{harvtxt|Balkan Society of Geometers|2011}} and of the {{harvtxt|Tensor Society|2010}}.</ref>\n\n===Personality traits===\n\n[[Enzo Martinelli]] describes Giovanni Battista Rizza as a passionate researcher with a \"strong intellectual force\",<ref name=\"Marp1\">{{harvtxt|Martinelli|1994|p=1}} precisely characterizes Rizza's scientific work as developed with \"''...molta passione e forza intellettuale...''\", i.e. with (English translation) \"...much passion and intellectual force...\".</ref> and his scientific work as rich of [[Geometry|geometrical]] ideas, denoting his strong [[algorithm]]ic ability.<ref>Again according to {{harvtxt|Martinelli|1995|p=2}}: \"Queste poche righe mi auguro siano servite a dimostrare che Rizza \u00e8 un matematico ricco di idee geometriche e dotato di forti capacit\u00e0 algoritmiche.\", i.e. (free English translation) \"I hope those few lines have been of some help in demonstrating that Rizza is a mathematician rich of geometrical ideas and gifted with a strong algorithmic ability.\"</ref> According to Martinelli, Rizza is also a skilled organizer:<ref name=\"Marp2\">See {{harv|Martinelli|1994|p=2}}.</ref> his ability in organizational tasks is also acknowledged and praised by {{harvtxt|Schreiber|1973|p=1}}, who also alludes the positive opinions of colleagues and students alike about his involvement in research, teaching and administrative duties at the mathematics department of the [[University of Parma]].\n\n==Work==\n\n===Research activity===\n\n[[File:Giovanni Battista Rizza.jpg|thumb|350px|right|Giovanni Battista Rizza at work in his home office, in 2003.]]\nGiovanni Battista Rizza has authored 53 research papers and 30 other scientific works, including research announcements, short notes, surveys and reports: he also wrote didactic notes and papers on historical topics, including commemorations of other scientists.<ref>See, for example, {{harv|Rizza|1984}}, {{harv|Rizza|1986}} and {{harv|Rizza|2002}}.</ref> His main fields of research are the [[Hypercomplex analysis|theory of functions on algebras]], the [[Several complex variables|theory of functions of several complex variables]], and [[differential geometry]].\n\n====Theory of functions on algebras====\n\nThe theory of functions on algebras, also referred to as [[hypercomplex analysis]], is the study of [[Function (mathematics)|function]]s whose [[Domain of a function|domain]] is a [[subset]] of an [[algebra over a field|algebra]].<ref>For more information see the survey article by {{harvtxt|Rizza|1973}} and the references cited therein.</ref> The first works of Giovanni Battista Rizza belong to this field of research, and he was awarded the [[Premio Ottorino Pomini]] for his contributions.<ref name=\"Pomini_motivation\" />\n\nHis first main result is the extension of [[Cauchy's integral theorem]] to every [[monogenic function]] {{math|F}} on a general [[algebra over a field|complex algebra]] {{math|'''''A'''''}},<ref>See {{harv|Rizza|1950}}.</ref>\n\n:<math>\\int_{\\Gamma_1} \\mathrm{F}(\\mathrm{X}) \\mathrm{d}\\mathrm{X}=0</math>\n\nwhere {{math|\u0393{{sub|1}}}} is a [[Cycle (algebraic topology)|1-dimensional cycle]] homologous to zero, and also satisfying other technical conditions.\n\nFew years later, he extended [[Cauchy's integral formula]] to every [[monogenic function]] {{math|F}} on a [[Commutative algebra (structure)|commutative]] [[Normed algebra|normed]] [[algebra over a field|real algebra]] {{math|'''''A'''''{{sup|*}}}},<ref>See {{harv|Rizza|1952}}, {{harv|Rizza|1952a}} and the survey {{harv|Rizza|1973}}.</ref> [[Isomorphism (algebra)|isomorphic]] to a given complex algebra {{math|'''''A'''''}}:<ref>In the terminology of {{harvs|txt|first=|last=Rizza|author1-link=|year=1952|year2=1952a}}, the algebra {{math|'''''A'''''{{sup|*}}}} is said to be the ''real image of''  (precisely, ''l'immagine reale di'') {{math|'''''A'''''}}.</ref> precisely, he proves the formula\n\n:<math>\\int_{\\Gamma_1}\\frac{\\mathrm{F}(\\mathrm{X})}{\\mathrm{X}-\\Xi}\\mathrm{d}\\mathrm{X}=2\\pi i\\sum^k_{s=1}\\mathrm{N}^{(s)}u^{(s)}\\mathrm{F}(\\Xi)</math>\n\nwhere\n*{{math|X&nbsp;\u2261&nbsp;''x''{{sup|*}}&nbsp;\u2261&nbsp;''x''}} identifies indifferently a [[Point (mathematics)|point]] in the complex algebra {{math|'''''A'''''}} or in its isomorphic real algebra {{math|'''''A'''''{{sup|*}}}},\n*{{math|\u0393{{sub|1}}}} is again a [[Cycle (algebraic topology)|1-dimensional cycle]] homologous to zero, and satisfying other technical conditions,\n*{{math|N{{sup|(''s'')}}}} is the [[winding number]] of the cycle {{math|\u0393{{sub|1}}}} respect to the [[zero divisor]] [[Locus (mathematics)|locus]] for the considered algebra.\n\n====Theory of analytic functions of several complex variables====\n\n{{quote\n|text= All'estensione, tutt'altro che banale, allo spazio {{math|''R''{{I sup|2''n''}}}} dei metodi di Martinelli per dimostrare la {{EquationNote|1|(3)}}, \u00e8 dedicata una Memoria [[#{{harvid|Rizza|1955}}|[8]]] di Giovanni Battista Rizza, il quale, sempre nell'ipotesi {{math|''\u03c1''(''x''{{sub|1}},&nbsp;''y''{{sub|1}},...,&nbsp;''x{{sub|n}}'',&nbsp;''y{{sub|n}}'')&nbsp;\u2208&nbsp;''C''{{I sup|\u03c9}}}}, perviene a stabilire la {{EquationNote|1|(3)}} per {{math|''n''}} qualsiasi. Anche questo lavoro, per quanto redatto in lingua inglese e pubblicato su una delle principali riviste matematiche, non ha nella letteratura attuale, la notoriet\u00e0 che meriterebbe.<ref>(English translation): \"To the far from trivial extension to the {{math|''R''{{I sup|2n}}}} space of Martinelli's methods in order to prove (3) a Memoir [8] of Giovanni Battista Rizza is devoted, who, again under the hypothesis that {{math|''\u03c1''(''x''{{sub|1}},&nbsp;''y''{{sub|1}},...,&nbsp;''x''{{sub|n}},&nbsp;''y''{{sub|n}})&nbsp;\u2208&nbsp;''C''{{I sup|\u03c9}}}}, succeeds in proving (3) for every {{math|''n''}}. Even this work, despite being written in English and published in a major mathematical journal, has not, in the current literature, the notoriety it deserves\".</ref>\n|sign= [[Gaetano Fichera]]\n|source= {{harv|Fichera|1982a|p=135}}.\n}}\nRizza published only three work in this field:<ref>The work {{harv|Rizza|1954}} is only a research announcement related to the {{harv|Rizza|1955}}, while {{harv|Rizza|1958}} is set of course notes based on the same paper and on {{harv|Rizza|1957}}.</ref> in the first one, the highly remarkable memoir {{harv|Rizza|1955}},<ref>According to {{harvtxt|Fichera|1982b|p=24}}, who praises this work as \"''molto considerevole''\": see also his comments in {{harv|Fichera|1982a|p=135}}.</ref> he extends to pluriharmonic functions of {{math|2''n''}} [[Function of a real variable|real variables]], {{math|''n''&nbsp;>&nbsp;2}}, the methods introduced by Enzo Martinelli in order to give new proof of a result of [[Luigi Amoroso]] for pluriharmonic functions of four real variables.<ref>See {{harv|Fichera|1982a|p=135}}, {{harv|Fichera|1982b|pp=24\u201325}} and {{harv|Martinelli|1941}}.</ref> Precisely, he proves the following formula\n\n{{NumBlk|::::::::::::::::::::|<math>\\frac{\\partial u}{\\partial \\nu} = \\frac{\\vert\\nabla \\rho\\vert^3}{Q(\\rho)} E u</math>|{{EquationRef|1}}}}\n\nwhere\n*{{math|''u''}} is a polyharmonic function defined on a [[Bounded set|bounded]] [[Domain (mathematical analysis)|domain]] {{math|\u03a9}},\n*{{math|''\u03c1''}} is a [[Real number|real]] [[analytic function]] defining the [[Boundary (topology)|boundary]] of {{math|\u03a9}} by the equation\n:<math>\\partial\\Omega = \\{x\\in\\mathbb{R}^{2n}|\\rho(x)=0\\},</math>\n*{{math|''Q''(''\u03c1'')}} is a linear combination of the [[CR manifold#The Levi form|Levi forms]] of {{math|''\u03c1''}} relative to couples of [[complex variable]]s,\n*{{math|''E''}} is a linear [[tangential operator]] defined on {{math|\u2202\u03a9}}.\nFormula {{EquationNote|1|(1)}} express a condition the [[normal derivative]] of the boundary value of a pluriharmonic function on domain with real analytic boundary must satisfy.<ref>See {{harv|Fichera|1982a|p=135}}, {{harv|Fichera|1982b|pp=24\u201325}} and {{harv|Fuks|1963|loc=p. 277, footnote 1}}.</ref> It can be used to construct an integral representation for pluriharmonic functions on such kind of domains, by using the [[Green's identities#Green's third identity|Green's formula]] for the [[Laplacian]],<ref>See {{harv|Fichera|1982a|p=134}}, {{harv|Fichera|1982b|p=33}} and {{harv|Martinelli|1941|p=162}}.</ref> and also to establish an [[integro-differential equation]] boundary values of pluriharmonic functions must satisfy.<ref>It is the [[Amoroso integro-differential equation]]: see {{harv|Fichera|1982a|p=134}} and {{harv|Fichera|1982b|pp=33}}.</ref> Rizza's result motivated other works on the same topic by Gaetano Fichera, Paolo de Bartolomeis and [[Giuseppe Tomassini]].<ref>See the hystorical survey sections in {{harv|Fichera|1982b|p=25}} and the work {{harv|de Bartolomeis|Tomassini|1981|p=33}}.</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n\n===Research works===\n\n*{{citation\n|last = Rizza\n|first = Giovanni Battista\n|author-link = \n|title = Sulle funzioni analitiche nelle algebre ipercomplesse\n|language = Italian\n|journal = [[Pontificia Academia Scientiarum. Commentationes]]\n|series =\n|volume = 14\n|issue = \n|year = 1950\n|pages = 169\u2013194\n|url = \n|doi = \n|mr = 57350\n|zbl = \n}}. In \"On analytic functions on hypercomplex algebras\" (English translation of the title), Rizza extends the classical Cauchy's integral theorem to monogenic functions on a general complex algebra.\n*{{citation\n|last = Rizza\n|first = Giovanni Battista\n|author-link = \n|title = Contributi al problema della determinazione di una formula integrale per le funzioni monogene nelle algebre complesse dotate di modulo e commutative\n|language = Italian\n|journal = [[Rendiconti di Matematica e delle sue Applicazioni|Rendiconti di Matematica]]\n|series = V Serie \n|volume = 23\n|issue = 1\u20132\n|year = 1952\n|pages = 134\u2013155\n|url = \n|doi = \n|mr = 0211370  \n|zbl = 0047.32204\n}}. \"Contributions to the problem of determining an integral formula for monogenic functions on complex commutative algebras with modulus\" (English translation of the title).\n*{{Citation\n|last = Rizza\n|first = Giovanni Battista\n|author-link = \n|title = Estensione della formula integrale di Cauchy alle algebre complesse dotate di modulo e commutative\n|language = Italian\n|journal = Rendiconti della Accademia Nazionale dei Lincei, Classe di Scienze Fisiche, Matematiche e Naturali\n|series = Serie VIII\n|volume = XII\n|issue = 6\n|pages = 667\u2013669\n|year = 1952a\n|mr = 0062240 \n|zbl = 0048.06101\n}}. \"Extension of Cauchy's integral formula to commutative complex algebras with modulus\" (English translation of the title).\n*{{citation\n|last = Rizza\n|first = Giovanni Battista\n|author-link = \n|title = Teoria delle funzioni nelle algebre complesse dotate di modulo e commutative\n|language = Italian\n|journal = [[Rendiconti di Matematica e delle sue Applicazioni|Rendiconti di Matematica]]\n|series = V Serie \n|volume = 23\n|issue = 1\u20132\n|year = 1953\n|pages = 221\u2013249\n|url = \n|doi = \n|mr = 0211370  \n|zbl = 0123.15203\n}}. \"Function theory on commutative complex algebras with modulus\" (English translation of the title).\n*{{Citation\n|last = Rizza\n|first = Giovanni Battista\n|author-link =\n|contribution = On Dirichlet's problem for components of analytic functions of several complex variables\n|contribution-url = http://www.mathunion.org/ICM/ICM1954.2/Main/icm1954.2.0160.0161.ocr.pdf\n|series = [[International Congress of Mathematicians|ICM Proceedings]]\n|title = Proceedings of the International Congress of Mathematicians, 1954. Volume II\n|pages = 161\u2013162\n|year = 1954\n|place = [[Amsterdam]]\u2013[[Groningen (city)|Groningen]]\n|publisher = [[Springer Science+Business Media|Erven P. Noordhoff N.V.]] / [[North-Holland Publishing Company]]\n|url = http://www.mathunion.org/ICM/ICM1954.2/\n|id =\n|mr =\n|zbl =\n}}. A short research announcement describing briefly the results proved in {{harv|Rizza|1955}}.\n*{{Citation\n|last = Rizza\n|first = G. B.\n|author-link =\n|title = Dirichlet problem for ''{{math|n}}''-harmonic functions and related geometrical problems\n|journal = [[Mathematische Annalen]]\n|volume = 130\n|issue = 3\n|pages = 202\u2013218\n|year = 1955\n|url = http://www.digizeitschriften.de/dms/img/?PPN=PPN235181684_0130&DMDID=dmdlog33\n|doi = 10.1007/BF01343349\n|id =\n|mr = 0074881\n|zbl = 0067.33004\n}}, available at [http://www.digizeitschriften.de/ DigiZeitschirften].\n*{{Citation\n|last = Rizza\n|first = G. B.\n|author-link =\n|title = Su diverse estensioni dell'invariante di E. E. Levi nella teoria delle funzioni di pi\u00f9 variabili complesse\n|language = Italian\n|journal=[[Annali di Matematica Pura ed Applicata]]\n|volume = 44\n|issue = 1\n|pages = 73\u201389\n|year = 1957\n|url =\n|doi = 10.1007/BF02415191\n|id =\n|mr = 0095965\n|zbl = 0091.25903\n}}. In the work \"''On different extensions of E. E. Levi invariant in the theory of functions of several complex variables''\" (English translation of the title), Rizza epitomizes all known extensions of the [[CR manifold#The Levi form|Levi invariant]] to [[hypersurface]]s in {{math|\u2102{{Sup|''n''}}}} for {{math|''n''&nbsp;>&nbsp;2}} in a single [[tensor]] of hybrid type. This paper is also interesting since it traces the story of such extensions back to the pioneering work of [[Eugenio Elia Levi]].\n*{{Citation\n|last = Rizza\n|first = G. B.\n|author-link =\n|editor-first = Francesco\n|editor-last = Severi\n|editor-link = Francesco Severi\n|contribution = Appendice I. Rappresentazione esplicita di tipo integrale per le funzioni ''{{math|r}}''\u2013armoniche. Estensione al caso di ''{{math|r}}'' variabili complesse dell'invariante di E. E. Levi\n|contribution-url =\n|title = Lezioni sulle funzioni analitiche di pi\u00f9 variabili complesse \u2013 Tenute nel 1956\u201357 all'Istituto Nazionale di Alta Matematica in Roma\n|language = Italian\n|place = Padova\n|publisher = CEDAM \u2013 Casa Editrice Dott. Antonio Milani\n|year = 1958\n|pages = 219\u2013231\n|url =\n|doi =\n|id =\n|zbl= 0094.28002\n|isbn = }}. The notes from the lectures given by Giovanni Battista Rizza for the course \"Lectures on analytic functions of several complex variables\", held by Francesco Severi at the [[Istituto Nazionale di Alta Matematica]]: the full course notes, published as a monograph, include also a chapter by Enzo Martinelli and an appendix by [[Mario Benedicty]]). The topics he exposes are summarized by the two parts of the title, whose English translations are \"Explicit integral representation for <math>r</math>\u2013harmonic functions\" and \"Extension of the [[CR manifold#The Levi form|E. E. Levi invariant]] to the case of <math>r</math> complex variables\".\n*{{Citation\n|last = Rizza\n|first = Giovanni Battista\n|author-link = \n|contribution = Finsler structures on almost complex manifolds\n|contribution-url = \n|series = [[International Congress of Mathematicians|ICM Proceedings]]\n|title = Proceedings of the International Congress of Mathematicians, Stockholm.\n|pages = \n|year = 1962a\n|place = [[Stockholm]]\n|publisher = \n|url = \n|id =\n|mr =\n|zbl =\n}}. A short research announcement describing briefly the results proved in {{harv|Rizza|1963}}.\n*{{Citation\n|last = Rizza\n|first = Giovanni Battista\n|author-link = \n|title = Strutture di Finsler sulle variet\u00e0 quasi complesse\n|language = Italian\n|journal = Rendiconti della Accademia Nazionale dei Lincei, Classe di Scienze Fisiche, Matematiche e Naturali\n|series = Serie VIII\n|volume = 33\n|issue = 5\n|pages = 271\u2013275\n|year = 1962b\n|mr = \n|zbl = \n}}. \"Finsler structures on almost complex manifolds\" (English translation of the title) is another short presentation of the results proved in {{harv|Rizza|1963}}.\n*{{Citation\n |last=Rizza \n |first=Giovanni Battista \n |title=Strutture di Finsler di tipo quasi Hermitiano \n |language=Italian \n |journal=Rivista di Matematica della Universit\u00e0 di Parma \n |series=(2) \n |volume=4 \n |pages=83\u2013106 \n |year=1963 \n |url=http://www.math.unipr.it/~rivista/dati/INDICI/indice63.html \n |mr=0166742 \n |zbl=0129.14101 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316160338/http://www.math.unipr.it/~rivista/dati/INDICI/indice63.html \n |archivedate=March 16, 2012 \n |df=mdy \n}}. The article giving the proofs of the results previously announced in references {{harv|Rizza|1962a}} and {{harvtxt|Rizza|1962b}}: the English translation of the title reads as: \"Finsler structures of almost Hermitian type\".\n*{{citation\n|last = Rizza\n|first = Giovanni Battista\n|author-link = \n|title = {{mvar|'''F'''}}-forme quadratiche ed hermitiane\n|language = Italian\n|journal = [[Rendiconti di Matematica e delle sue Applicazioni|Rendiconti di Matematica]]\n|series = V Serie \n|volume = 23\n|issue = 1\u20132\n|year = 1964\n|pages = 221\u2013249\n|url = \n|doi = \n|mr = 0211370  \n|zbl = 0123.15203\n}}. This article is the one [[Shoshichi Kobayashi]] cites as the first one in the theory of Rizza manifolds: an English translation of the title reads as: \"Hermitian and quadratic {{mvar|'''F'''}}-forms\".\n*{{Citation\n|last = Rizza\n|first = Giovanni Battista\n|author-link =\n|title =Teoremi di rappresentazione per alcune classi di connessioni su di una variet\u00e0 quasi complessa\n|journal = [[Rendiconti dell'Istituto di Matematica dell'Universit\u00e0 di Trieste]] \n|volume = 1\n|pages =  9\u201325\n|year = 1969\n|language = Italian\n|url = http://rendiconti.dmi.units.it/volumi/01/02.pdf\n|doi =\n|id =\n|mr = 257917\n|zbl =0183.50701\n}}.\n*{{Citation\n|last = Rizza\n|first = Giovanni Battista\n|author-link =\n|title =Connessioni metriche sulle variet\u00e0 quasi hermitiane\n|journal = [[Rendiconti dell'Istituto di Matematica dell'Universit\u00e0 di Trieste]] \n|volume = 1\n|pages =  9\u201325\n|year = 1969\n|language = Italian\n|url = http://rendiconti.dmi.units.it/volumi/01/15.pdf\n|doi =\n|id =\n|mr = 262995\n|zbl =0192.58903\n}}. \n*{{Citation\n|last = Dentoni\n|first = Paolo\n|author-link = \n|last2 = Rizza\n|first2 = Giovanni Battista\n|author2-link =\n|title = Una nuova classe di funzioni in un'algebra reale\n|journal = [[Rendiconti dell'Istituto di Matematica dell'Universit\u00e0 di Trieste]] \n|volume = 4\n|pages =  171\u2013181\n|year = 1972\n|language = Italian\n|url = http://rendiconti.dmi.units.it/volumi/04/17.pdf\n|doi =\n|id =\n|mr = 492318\n|zbl = 0251.30050\n}}. \"A new class of functions on a real algebra\" (English translation of the title) the authors introduce a new class of functions on a real algebra in the attempt of unifying the research trends on functions on real algebras in the seventies.\n\n===Historical, commemorative and survey papers===\n\n*{{Citation\n| last = Rizza\n|first = Giovanni Battista\n|author-link =\n|title = Contributi recenti alla teoria delle funzioni nelle algebre\n|journal = [[Rendiconti del Seminario Matematico e Fisico di Milano]]\n|volume = 43\n|issue = 1\n|pages = 45\u201354\n|date = 12 December 1973\n|language = Italian\n|doi = 10.1007/BF02924838\n|id =\n|mr = 0350025\n|zbl = 0325.30040\n}}. \"Recent contributions to the theory of functions on algebras\" (English translation of the title) is a short but comprehensive survey paper detailing the works on the field done by Italian mathematicians during the years from 1961 to 1973: however, it also includes several biographical references to other earlier works by non Italian mathematicians and to historical bibliographies on hypercomplex analysis.\n*{{Citation\n|first = Giovanni Battista\n|last = Rizza\n|author-link = \n|editor-last 