le \u2013 Parma, 19\u201320 maggio 1994 in occasione del 70\u00b0 compleanno di G. B. Rizza\n  | language = Italian\n  | publisher = [[Rivista di Matematica della Universit\u00e0 di Parma]]\n  | series = 5<sup>a</sup> Serie\n  | volume = 3\n  | issue = I\n  | year = 1994\n  | pages = 1\u20132\n  | url = http://rivista.math.unipr.it/vols/1994-3-I/indice.html\n  | id =\n  | mr =\n  | zbl =\n}}. \"Homage to Giovanni Battista Rizza on his 70th birthday\" (English translation of the title) a tribute to Giovanni Battista Rizza by his former master [[Enzo Martinelli]].\n*{{Citation\n  | last = Il Ministro dell'Universit\u00e0 e della Ricerca Scientifica e Tecnologica\n  | author-link = Ministry of Education, Universities and Research\n  | title = Decreto Ministeriale 17 Febbraio 1999\n  | date = 19 February 1999\n  | language = Italian\n  | url = \n  | accessdate =}}. The \"Ministerial Decree\" awarding the title of \"Professor Emeritus\" to Giovanni Battista Rizza.\n*{{Citation\n  | last = Presidenza della Repubblica Italiana\n  | author-link =\n  | title = Medaglia d'oro ai benemeriti della scuola della cultura e dell'arte: Giovanni Battista Rizza\n  | date = 31 July 1973\n  | url = http://www.quirinale.it/elementi/DettaglioOnorificenze.aspx?decorato=8067\n  | accessdate = 31 May 2011}}.\n*{{Citation\n  | last = Rivista di Matematica della Universit\u00e0 di Parma\n  | first = (the Editorial Board of)\n  | author-link = \n  | title = History\n  | date = 12 December 2013\n  | url = http://rivista.math.unipr.it/aboutus.html\n  | accessdate = 12 January 2013\n}}.\n*{{Citation\n  | last = Roghi\n  | first = G.\n  | author-link = Gino Roghi\n  | title = Materiale per una storia dell'Istituto Nazionale di Alta Matematica dal 1939 to 2003.\n  | journal = [[Bollettino della Unione Matematica Italiana|Bollettino della Unione Matematica Italiana, Sezione A, La Matematica nella Societ\u00e0 e nella Cultura]]\n  | series = Serie VIII\n  | volume = 8-A\n  | issue = 3, parte 2\n  | pages = x+301\n  |date=December 2005\n  | language = Italian\n  | url =\n  | doi =\n  | mr = 2225078\n  | zbl = 1089.01500\n}}. \"Materials toward a history of the Istituto Nazionale di Alta Matematica from 1939 to 2003\" (English translation of title) is a [[monograph]]ic [[Serial (literature)|fascicle]] published on the \"Bollettino della Unione Matematica Italiana\", describing the history of the [[Istituto Nazionale di Alta Matematica Francesco Severi]] from its foundation in 1939 to 2003. It was written by [[Gino Roghi]] and includes a presentation by Salvatore Coen and a preface by [[Corrado De Concini]]. It is almost exclusively based on [[Information source|sources]] from the institute archives: the wealth and variety of materials included, jointly with its [[Addendum#In books|appendices]] and [[Index (publishing)|indexes]], make this monograph a useful reference not only for the history of the [[institute]] itself, but also for the history of many [[mathematician]]s who taught, followed the institute courses or simply worked there.\n*{{Citation\n | last = Schreiber\n | first = Bruno\n | author-link =\n | title = Curriculum Vit\u00e6 di Giambattista Rizza\n | publisher = Istituto di Matematica dell'Universit\u00e0 di Parma\n | pages = 4\n | year = 1973\n | month =\n | language = Italian\n | url =\n}}. The official 1973 CV of Giovanni Battista Rizza, available from the Institute of Mathematics of the University of Parma.\n*{{Citation\n  | last = Tensor Society \n  | author-link = Tensor Society\n  | title = List of life members of the Tensor Society\n  | year = 2010\n  | url = http://www.tensorsociety.org/images/Life-Members.pdf\n  | accessdate = 14 July 2013\n}}.\n*{{Citation\n | first = Giancarlo\n | last = Venturini \n | author-link =\n | contribution = Prolusione all'apertura dell'A.A. 1962/63\n | contribution-url =\n | title = Annuario dell'Universit\u00e0 di Parma\n | volume = A.A. 1962/63\n | year = 1963\n | place = [[Parma]]\n | publisher = [[Universit\u00e0 degli Studi di Parma]]\n | url =\n | doi =\n}}. The opening address on the occasion of the beginning of the [[academic year]] 1962/63, given by the [[Rector (academic)|Magnifico Rettore]] prof. G. Venturini.\n\n===Scientific references===\n\n*{{Citation\n  | last = Aikou\n  | first = Tadashi \n  | author-link = \n  | editor-last = Bao\n  | editor-first = David\n  | editor2-last = Bryant\n  | editor2-first = Robert L. | editor2-link = Robert Bryant (mathematician)\n  | editor3-last = Chern\n  | editor3-first = Shiing-Shen\n  | editor3-link = Shiing-Shen Chern\n  | editor4-last = Shen\n  | editor4-first = Zhongmin\n  | contribution = Finsler Geometry on Complex Vector Bundles\n  | contribution-url = http://library.msri.org/books/Book50/files/04Ai.pdf\n  | title = A Sampler of Riemann\u2013Finsler Geometry\n  | place = Cambridge\n  | publisher = [[Cambridge University Press]]\n  | series = Mathematical Sciences Research Institute Publications\n  | volume = 50\n  | year = 2004\n  | pages = 83\u2013105 \n  | language = \n  | url = http://library.msri.org/books/Book50/contents.html\n  | doi = \n  | id = \n  | isbn = 978-0-521-83181-9\n  | mr = 2132658 \n  | zbl = 1073.53093 \n| bibcode = 2004srfg.book.....B \n }}.\n*{{Citation\n | last =de Bartolomeis\n | first = Paolo\n | author-link =\n | last2 =Tomassini\n | first2 =Giuseppe\n | author2-link =Giuseppe Tomassini\n | title =Traces of pluriharmonic functions\n | journal =[[Compositio Mathematica]]\n | volume =44\n | issue =1\u20133\n | pages =29\u201339\n | year =1981\n | url =http://www.numdam.org/item?id=CM_1981__44_1-3_29_0\n | mr =662454\n | zbl =0484.32007\n}}.\n*{{Citation\n  | editor-last = Donnini\n  | editor-first = S.\n  | editor2-last = Gigante\n  | editor2-first = G.\n  | editor3-last = Mangione\n  | editor3-first = V.\n  | title = Geometria differenziale \u2013 Analisi complessa. Convegno internazionale \u2013 Parma, 19\u201320 maggio 1994 in occasione del 70\u00b0 compleanno di G. B. Rizza\n  | journal=Rivista di Matematica della Universit\u00e0 di Parma\n  | series = Serie 5\n  | volume = 3\n  | number = Parte I\n  | year = 1994\n  | url = http://rivista.math.unipr.it/vols/1994-3-I/indice.html\n  | id =\n}}. The [[proceedings]] of the international [[meeting]] \"Differential Geometry \u2013 Complex analysis\" held in Parma on May 19\u201320, 1994 to celebrate Giovanni Battista Rizza's 70th birthday, published by the [[Rivista di Matematica della Universit\u00e0 di Parma]]. The first speaker was his former master [[Enzo Martinelli]].\n*{{Citation\n| first = Gaetano\n| last = Fichera\n| author-link= Gaetano Fichera\n| contribution = Problemi al contorno per le funzioni pluriarmoniche \n| title = Atti del Convegno celebrativo dell'80\u00b0 anniversario della nascita di Renato Calapso, Messina\u2013Taormina, 1\u20134 aprile 1981\n| year = 1982a\n| pages = 127\u2013152\n| language = Italian\n| place = Roma\n| publisher = Libreria Eredi Virgilio Veschi\n| mr = 0698973 \n| zbl = 0958.32504\n}}. \"Boundary value problems for pluriharmonic functions\" (English translation of the title) deals with [[boundary value problem]]s for pluriharmonic functions: Fichera gives a [[Trace operator|trace condition]] for the solvability of the problem and extensively reviews its history, starting from its beginning in the work of [[Henri Poincare]] and analyzing several earlier results of Enzo Martinelli, Giovanni Battista Rizza and Francesco Severi, as well as works of [[Aldo Andreotti]] among the others.\n*{{Citation\n| last = Fichera\n| first = Gaetano\n| title = Valori al contorno delle funzioni pluriarmoniche: estensione allo spazio {{math|''R''<sup>2''n''</sup>}} di un teorema di L. Amoroso \n| journal = [[Milan Journal of Mathematics|Rendiconti del Seminario Matematico e Fisico di Milano]]\n| volume = 52\n| issue = 1\n| pages = 23\u201334\n| year = 1982b\n| language = Italian\n| doi = 10.1007/BF02924996\n| id = \n| mr = 0802991\n| zbl= 0569.31006\n}}. In the work \"Boundary values of pluriharmonic functions: extension to the space {{math|''R''<sup>2''n''</sup>}}  of a theorem of L. Amoroso\" (English translation of the title), Gaetano Fichera proves anothera trace condition for pluriharmonic functions and surveys other recent works in the fields, notably the one of {{harvtxt|de Bartolomeis|Tomassini|1981}}.\n*{{Citation\n  | last = Fuks\n  | first = B. A.\n  | author-link = Boris Abramovich Fuks\n  | title = Introduction to the Theory of Analytic Functions of Several Complex Variables\n  | place = Providence, RI\n  | publisher = [[American Mathematical Society]] \n  | series = Translations of Mathematical Monographs\n  | volume = 8\n  | year = 1963\n  | pages = vi+374\n  | language = \n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=OSlWYzf2FcwC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=true\n  | doi = \n  | id = \n  | isbn = 9780821886441\n  | mr = 0168793 \n  | zbl = 0138.30902 \n}}.\n*{{Citation\n |last=Ichijy\u014d \n |first=Yoshihiro \n |title=Finsler metrics on almost complex manifolds \n |journal=Rivista di Matematica della Universit\u00e0 di Parma \n |series=(IV) \n |volume=14* \n |pages=1\u201328 \n |year=1988 \n |url=http://www.math.unipr.it/~rivista/dati/INDICI/indspe88.html \n |mr=1045035 \n |zbl=0885.53031 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316160352/http://www.math.unipr.it/~rivista/dati/INDICI/indspe88.html \n |archivedate=March 16, 2012 \n |df=mdy \n}}.\n*{{Citation\n  | last = Kobayashi\n  | first = Shoshichi\n  | author-link = Shoshichi Kobayashi\n  | title = Negative vector bundles and complex Finsler structures\n  | journal=Nagoya Mathematical Journal\n  | volume = 57\n  | pages = 153\u2013166\n  | year = 1975\n  | url = http://projecteuclid.org/euclid.nmj/1118795367\n  | id =\n  | mr = 0377126\n  | zbl = 0326.32016\n| doi = 10.1017/S0027763000016615\n  }}. In this paper, [[Shoshichi Kobayashi]] acknowledges Giovanni Battista Rizza as the first one to study [[complex manifold]]s with [[Finsler manifold|Finsler structure]], now called [[Rizza manifold]]s.\n*{{Citation\n | last1=Martinelli \n | first1=Enzo \n | author-link= Enzo Martinelli\n | title=Studio di alcune questioni della teoria delle funzioni biarmoniche e delle funzioni analitiche di due variabili complesse coll'ausilio del calcolo differenziale assoluto\n | language = Italian\n | year=1941\n | journal=[[Atti della Reale Accademia d'Italia. Memorie della Classe di Scienze Fisiche, Matematiche e Naturali]]\n | issue=4\n | volume=12\n | pages=143\u2013167\n | id= \n | jfm= 67.0299.01\n | mr=0017810\n | zbl = 0025.40503\n}}. In \"Study of some questions of the theory of biharmonic functions and of analytic functions of two complex variables by using the absolute differential calculus\" (English translation of title) Martinelli proves an earlier result of [[Luigi Amoroso]] on the boundary values of pluriharmonic function by using [[tensor calculus]].\n*{{Citation\n | last =Scharnhorst\n | first =K.\n | author-link =\n | title =Angles in Complex Vector Spaces\n | journal =[[Acta Applicandae Mathematicae]]\n | volume =69\n | issue =1\n | pages =95\u2013103\n | year =2001\n | url =\n | doi =10.1023/A:1012692601098\n | id =\n | mr =1868915 \n | zbl =0993.51010\n| arxiv =math/9904077}}.\n*{{Citation\n| last = Severi\n| first = Francesco\n| author-link = Francesco Severi\n| title = Lezioni sulle funzioni analitiche di pi\u00f9 variabili complesse \u2013 Tenute nel 1956\u201357 all'Istituto Nazionale di Alta Matematica in Roma\n| place = Padova\n| publisher = [[Casa Editrice Dottor Antonio Milani|CEDAM \u2013 Casa Editrice Dott. Antonio Milani]]\n| year = 1958\n| pages = XIV+255\n| language = Italian\n| url =\n| doi =\n| id =\n| zbl= 0094.28002\n| isbn = }}. The \"Lectures on analytic functions of several complex variables \u2013 Lectured in 1956\u201357 at the Istituto Nazionale di Alta Matematica in Rome\" (English translation of the title) is a set of lecture notes from a course held by Francesco Severi at the [[Istituto Nazionale di Alta Matematica]], including appendices of Enzo Martinelli, Giovanni Battista Rizza and [[Mario Benedicty]].\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rizza, Giovanni Battista}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Italian mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Italian mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Complex analysts]]\n[[Category:Differential geometers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mathematical analysts]]\n[[Category:University of Genoa alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Parma faculty]]\n[[Category:People from Piazza Armerina]]\n", "name_user": "TheAwesomeHwyh", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Information source\u2192source text", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Giovanni_Battista_Rizza"}
{"title_page": "Charis Kostakis", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name     = Charis Kostakis\n| fullname = Charilaos Kostakis\n| image =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1990|7|12}}\n| birth_place = [[Ioannina]], Greece\n| height = {{height|m=1.75}}\n| position = [[Midfield (association football)|Midfielder]]\n| currentclub  =\n| clubnumber =\n| youthyears1 = 2005\u20132006\n| youthclubs1 = [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]]\n| youthyears2 = 2006\u20132007\n| youthclubs2 = [[Zeeburgia]]\n| youthyears3 = 2007\u20132009\n| youthclubs3 = [[Telstar (football club)|Stormvogels Telstar]]\n| years1 = 2009\u20132011\n| clubs1 = [[Ethnikos Piraeus F.C.|Ethnikos Piraeus]]\n| caps1 = 30\n| goals1 = 1\n| years2 = 2011\u20132012\n| clubs2 = [[FK Mlad\u00e1 Boleslav|Mlad\u00e1 Boleslav]]\n| caps2 = 3\n| goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2012\n| clubs3 = [[Iraklis Thessaloniki F.C.|Iraklis]]\n| caps3 = 12\n| goals3 = 1\n| years4 = 2012\u20132013\n| clubs4 = [[PAS Giannina F.C.|PAS Giannina]]\n| caps4 = 0\n| goals4 = 0\n| years5 = 2013\n| clubs5 = [[NK Dom\u017eale|Dom\u017eale]]\n| caps5 = 5\n| goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2013\u20132015\n| clubs6 = [[Panionios]]\n| caps6 = 0\n| goals6 = 0\n| years7 = 2015\n| clubs7 = [[A.O.T. Alimos F.C.|Alimos]]\n| caps7 = 0\n| goals7 = 0\n| nationalyears1 =\n| nationalteam1 = [[Greece national under-17 football team|Greece U17]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 3\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| pcupdate = 06:41, 23 May 2013 (UTC)\n| ntupdate = 17:17, 14 January 2013 (UTC)\n}}\n\n'''Charis Kostakis''' ({{lang-el|\u03a7\u03ac\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03c9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2}}; born 12 July 1990) is a [[Greece|Greek]] former professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a midfielder.\n\n==Career==\nAlthough he was born in [[Ioannina]], Kostakis began playing football in the youth system of [[AFC Ajax|Ajax Amsterdam]] at age 15. Ajax loaned him to Dutch amateur side [[Telstar (football club)|Stormvogels Telstar]] at age 19. Soon after, Kostakis returned to Greece and joined [[Football League (Greece)|Greek second division]] club [[Ethnikos Piraeus F.C.]] on a three-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Ethnikos.gr|script-title=el:\u03a0\u03bf\u03b4\u03cc\u03c3\u03c6\u03b1\u03b9\u03c1\u03bf, \u039d\u03b1\u03c5\u03ac\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf \u03bc\u03b5 \u039a\u03c1\u03b9\u03c0\u03b9\u03bd\u03c4\u03af\u03c1\u03b7, \u03c0\u03ae\u03c1\u03b5 \u039a\u03c9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7|url=http://www.ethnikos.gr/Football-Nea-2009-10/Kostakis_05-07-09.htm|language=Greek|date=5 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2011, Kostakis joined the [[Czech Cup]]-winning side [[FK Mlad\u00e1 Boleslav]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Sport-FM|script-title=el:\u03a3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03a4\u03c3\u03b5\u03c7\u03af\u03b1 \u03bf \u039a\u03c9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2!|url=http://www.sport-fm.gr/article/491554|language = Greek | date = 1 August 2011 }}</ref><ref>http://www.fkmb.cz/clanky.php?article=6254</ref>\n\nIn January 2012, Kostakis joined [[Iraklis Thessaloniki F.C.]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Sport-FM|script-title=el:\"\u0393\u03b9\u03bf\u03c1\u03c4\u03ae\" \u03bc\u03b5 \u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03ae \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1\u2026 \u0391\u0395\u03a0 \u0397\u03c1\u03b1\u03ba\u03bb\u03ae!|url=http://www.sport-fm.gr/article/528168|language=Greek|date=18 January 2012}}</ref> and in the following summer he was transferred to [[Greek Superleague]] [[PAS Giannina F.C.]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Kintis|first=Vasilis|title=Kostakis at PAS|url=http://www.dailygoal.gr/shownews.php?new_id=2397|publisher=Daily Goal|accessdate=10 January 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130405053627/http://dailygoal.gr/shownews.php?new_id=2397|archivedate=5 April 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Moreover, he has played for [[NK Dom\u017eale]] in the [[Slovenian PrvaLiga]].<ref>{{cite web|title=V Dom\u017eale prihaja biv\u0161i \u010dlan Ajaxa, Charis Kostakis|url=http://offside.si/v-domzale-prihaja-bivsi-clan-ajaxa-charis-kostakis/|publisher=Offside|accessdate=12 January 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116112234/http://offside.si/v-domzale-prihaja-bivsi-clan-ajaxa-charis-kostakis/|archivedate=16 January 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nKostakis has also played for the [[Greece national under-17 football team|Greece under-17 national team]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{soccerway}}\n*[http://www.epae.org/player.fds?categ=2&team=140&player=12257&pagecode=04.02.02&langid=1 Profile at EPAE.org] {{in lang|el}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140308104509/http://myplayer.gr/index.php?option=com_myplayer_players&view=player&player=449 Myplayer.gr Profile] {{in lang|el}}\n*{{Fotbal DNES|id=3011131}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120324225107/http://www.fkmb.eu/club/hrac.php?s=2012&=1&p=522 FKMB profile] {{in lang|cs}}\n*[http://www.prvaliga.si/klubi/mostvo/igralec.asp?idi=105072&id=27&all=1 PrvaLiga profile] {{in lang|sl}}\n*[http://www.nogomania.com/Mednarodni-Nogomet/Igralec/Charis-Kostakis.aspx Nogomania profile] {{in lang|sl}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kostakis, Charis}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Greek footballers]]\n[[Category:Greek expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Slovenia]]\n[[Category:Ethnikos Piraeus F.C. players]]\n[[Category:FK Mlad\u00e1 Boleslav players]]\n[[Category:Iraklis Thessaloniki F.C. players]]\n[[Category:PAS Giannina F.C. players]]\n[[Category:NK Dom\u017eale players]]\n[[Category:Panionios F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name     = Charis Kostakis\n| fullname = Charilaos Kostakis\n| image =\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1990|7|12}}\n| birth_place = [[Ioannina]], Greece\n| height = {{height|m=1.75}}\n| position = [[Midfield (association football)|Midfielder]]\n| currentclub  =\n| clubnumber =\n| youthyears1 = 2005\u20132006\n| youthclubs1 = [[AFC Ajax|Ajax]]\n| youthyears2 = 2006\u20132007\n| youthclubs2 = [[Zeeburgia]]\n| youthyears3 = 2007\u20132009\n| youthclubs3 = [[Telstar (football club)|Stormvogels Telstar]]\n| years1 = 2009\u20132011\n| clubs1 = [[Ethnikos Piraeus F.C.|Ethnikos Piraeus]]\n| caps1 = 30\n| goals1 = 1\n| years2 = 2011\u20132012\n| clubs2 = [[FK Mlad\u00e1 Boleslav|Mlad\u00e1 Boleslav]]\n| caps2 = 3\n| goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2012\n| clubs3 = [[Iraklis Thessaloniki F.C.|Iraklis]]\n| caps3 = 12\n| goals3 = 1\n| years4 = 2012\u20132013\n| clubs4 = [[PAS Giannina F.C.|PAS Giannina]]\n| caps4 = 0\n| goals4 = 0\n| years5 = 2013\n| clubs5 = [[NK Dom\u017eale|Dom\u017eale]]\n| caps5 = 5\n| goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2013\u20132015\n| clubs6 = [[Panionios]]\n| caps6 = 0\n| goals6 = 0\n| years7 = 2015\n| clubs7 = [[A.O.T. Alimos F.C.|Alimos]]\n| caps7 = 0\n| goals7 = 0\n| nationalyears1 =\n| nationalteam1 = [[Greece national under-17 football team|Greece U17]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 3\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| pcupdate = 06:41, 23 May 2013 (UTC)\n| ntupdate = 17:17, 14 January 2013 (UTC)\n}}\n\n'''Charis Kostakis''' ({{lang-el|\u03a7\u03ac\u03c1\u03b7\u03c2 \u039a\u03c9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2}}; born 12 July 1990) is a [[Greece|Greek]] former professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a midfielder.\n\n==Career==\nAlthough he was born in [[Ioannina]], Kostakis began playing football in the youth system of [[AFC Ajax|Ajax Amsterdam]] at age 15. Ajax loaned him to Dutch amateur side [[Telstar (football club)|Stormvogels Telstar]] at age 19. Soon after, Kostakis returned to Greece and joined [[Football League (Greece)|Greek second division]] club [[Ethnikos Piraeus F.C.]] on a three-year contract.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Ethnikos.gr|script-title=el:\u03a0\u03bf\u03b4\u03cc\u03c3\u03c6\u03b1\u03b9\u03c1\u03bf, \u039d\u03b1\u03c5\u03ac\u03b3\u03b9\u03bf \u03bc\u03b5 \u039a\u03c1\u03b9\u03c0\u03b9\u03bd\u03c4\u03af\u03c1\u03b7, \u03c0\u03ae\u03c1\u03b5 \u039a\u03c9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7|url=http://www.ethnikos.gr/Football-Nea-2009-10/Kostakis_05-07-09.htm|language=Greek|date=5 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2011, Kostakis joined the [[Czech Cup]]-winning side [[FK Mlad\u00e1 Boleslav]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Sport-FM|script-title=el:\u03a3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03a4\u03c3\u03b5\u03c7\u03af\u03b1 \u03bf \u039a\u03c9\u03c3\u03c4\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2!|url=http://www.sport-fm.gr/article/491554|language = Greek | date = 1 August 2011 }}</ref><ref>http://www.fkmb.cz/clanky.php?article=6254</ref>\n\nIn January 2012, Kostakis joined [[Iraklis Thessaloniki F.C.]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Sport-FM|script-title=el:\"\u0393\u03b9\u03bf\u03c1\u03c4\u03ae\" \u03bc\u03b5 \u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03b3\u03c1\u03b1\u03c6\u03ae \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1\u2026 \u0391\u0395\u03a0 \u0397\u03c1\u03b1\u03ba\u03bb\u03ae!|url=http://www.sport-fm.gr/article/528168|language=Greek|date=18 January 2012}}</ref> and in the following summer he was transferred to [[Greek Superleague]] [[PAS Giannina F.C.]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Kintis|first=Vasilis|title=Kostakis at PAS|url=http://www.dailygoal.gr/shownews.php?new_id=2397|publisher=Daily Goal|accessdate=10 January 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130405053627/http://dailygoal.gr/shownews.php?new_id=2397|archivedate=5 April 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Moreover, he has played for [[NK Dom\u017eale]] in the [[Slovenian PrvaLiga]].<ref>{{cite web|title=V Dom\u017eale prihaja biv\u0161i \u010dlan Ajaxa, Charis Kostakis|url=http://offside.si/v-domzale-prihaja-bivsi-clan-ajaxa-charis-kostakis/|publisher=Offside|accessdate=12 January 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116112234/http://offside.si/v-domzale-prihaja-bivsi-clan-ajaxa-charis-kostakis/|archivedate=16 January 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nKostakis has also played for the [[Greece national under-17 football team|Greece under-17 national team]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.scoresway.com/?sport=soccer&page=player&id=173004 Scoresway.com Profile]\n*[http://www.epae.org/player.fds?categ=2&team=140&player=12257&pagecode=04.02.02&langid=1 Profile at EPAE.org] {{in lang|el}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140308104509/http://myplayer.gr/index.php?option=com_myplayer_players&view=player&player=449 Myplayer.gr Profile] {{in lang|el}}\n*{{Fotbal DNES|id=3011131}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120324225107/http://www.fkmb.eu/club/hrac.php?s=2012&=1&p=522 FKMB profile] {{in lang|cs}}\n*[http://www.prvaliga.si/klubi/mostvo/igralec.asp?idi=105072&id=27&all=1 PrvaLiga profile] {{in lang|sl}}\n*[http://www.nogomania.com/Mednarodni-Nogomet/Igralec/Charis-Kostakis.aspx Nogomania profile] {{in lang|sl}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kostakis, Charis}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Greek footballers]]\n[[Category:Greek expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in the Czech Republic]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Slovenia]]\n[[Category:Ethnikos Piraeus F.C. players]]\n[[Category:FK Mlad\u00e1 Boleslav players]]\n[[Category:Iraklis Thessaloniki F.C. players]]\n[[Category:PAS Giannina F.C. players]]\n[[Category:NK Dom\u017eale players]]\n[[Category:Panionios F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n", "name_user": "Pelmeen10", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charis_Kostakis"}
{"title_page": "Siouxsie Q", "text_new": "{{short description|American journalist, pornographic actress and outspoken sex workers\u2019 rights activist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Siouxsie Q\n| image         = Siouxsie Q 2019 by Glenn Francis.jpg\n| alt           = face of a woman with dark brown hair and brown eyes wearing a gold necklace looking at the camera \n| caption       = Siouxsie Q in Hollywood in October 2019\n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year with {{Birth year and age|YYYY}} unless the exact date is already widely published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = \n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = \n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}'''Siouxsie Q''' is an American journalist, pornographic actress, and outspoken [[sex workers' rights|sex workers\u2019 rights]] activist who identifies herself as a [[feminist]] and [[sex worker]]. She is a podcaster, singer/songwriter and playwright as well as a widely read columnist with [[SF Weekly]] in San Francisco.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Levine|first1=Katie|title=Sex Nerd Sandra #136: Sex Work with Siouxsie Q plus Matt Kirshen|url=http://www.nerdist.com/pepisode/sex-nerd-sandra-136-sex-work-with-siouxsie-q-plus-matt-kirshen/|website=The Nerdist|accessdate=26 June 2014|date=2014-03-26}}</ref>\n\n== Personal ==\nSiouxsie Q is based in San Francisco and is married to fellow podcaster and journalist Jesse James. They have a [[Polyamory|polyamorous]] relationship.<ref>{{cite|last= Siouxsie Q|date= 2016|title= Truth, Justice and the American Whore|publisher= ThreeL Media|isbn= 0990557154}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAfter appearing on amateur sites Dare Ring and being a contributor to the sellyoursextape videos (Ashley & Dakota) In 2010, Siouxsie Q left her retail job and began dancing at [[Lusty Lady|The Lusty Lady Theater]], a unionized peep show in North Beach, San Francisco.<ref>{{cite web|title=SF Fringe Festival to Offer Sex-Worker Siouxsie Q's FISH-GIRL|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/san-francisco/article/SF-Fringe-Festival-to-Offer-Sex-Worker-Siouxsie-Qs-FISH-GIRL-More-96-21-20130731?%3E-page2# |website=Broadway World|accessdate=26 June 2014}}</ref> Shortly after, she began her career as a sex worker while living in Inner Richmond, commuting to an apartment in East Bay to conduct business.\n\nInitially using the Internet primarily as a marketing tool, Siouxsie has stated that podcasts have \"really transformed how I do business.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Carroll|first1=Rory|title=Sex and Silicon Valley: the veritable arms race of the dating app industry|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jun/22/sex-silicon-valley-veritable-arms-race-dating-apps|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=29 June 2014|date=2014-06-22}}</ref> By 2012, she had settled into her career and, at the urging of her boyfriend, began a regular, biweekly podcast as a way to speak out against California's Proposition 35, Measure B. Originally called, \u201cThis American Whore,\u201d the podcast's name was eventually changed to \u201cThe WhoreCast\u201d after a dispute with \"[[This American Life]],\" the public radio program.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|authorlink=Laurie Segall|last1=Segall|first1=Laurie|last2=Fink|first2=Erica|title=Silicon Valley's other entrepreneurs: Sex workers|url=http://money.cnn.com/2013/04/15/technology/silicon-valley-sex-workers/|website=CNN Money|accessdate=25 June 2014|date=2013-04-15}}</ref> After the passing of Proposition 35, the podcast was expanded to cover a broad range of topics such as transgender issues, sexuality, sex workers\u2019 rights, politics and pornography.\n\nIn 2014, she began writing a regular column for SF Weekly in which she discusses the topics of pornography, feminism, sexuality and the sex work industry.\n\nShe was jointly nominated for Best All-Girl Group Sex Scene at the 2015 [[AVN Award]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://avnawards.avn.com/pages/4 |title=2016 AVN Awards|work=AVN|accessdate=22 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Political views ==\nBy way of her podcast, \u201cThe WhoreCast,\u201d Siouxsie Q emerged as an outspoken opponent of [[California elections, November 2012|California's Proposition 35]], Measure B, a part of the \u201cCalifornians Against Sexual Exploitation Act.\u201d In her broadcasts, she stated that she considered the proposition \u201ca confusing piece of legislation\u201d that too broadly expanded the definition of \u201ctrafficking\u201d to include anyone who lived with or derived support from someone who is a prostitute.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Q|first1=Siouxsie|title=Confessions of an American Whore: Sex Work Holds a Mirror Up to S.F.'s Hidden Kinks and Communities|url=http://www.sfweekly.com/2014-01-29/news/siouxsie-q-sex-workers-lusty-lady-fetish/|website=SF Weekly|accessdate=25 June 2014}}</ref> In response, The WhoreCast was established as \u201ca vehicle to really humanize sex work\u201d and as a way to oppose Proposition 35.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\nShe also utilized the podcast to speak out against [[Measure B|Assembly Bill 1576]], a bill that would require condoms be worn in all adult films made in California. She described the bill as \u201cpart of a multipronged strategy [\u2026] to shut down the porn industry in California.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|last1=Q|first1=Siouxsie|title=The Rubber State: Porn Finds the Condom Bill Ill-Fitting|url=http://www.sfweekly.com/2014-05-28/culture/whore-next-door-condom-bill-porn/|website=SF Weekly|accessdate=25 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The WhoreCast: Stop AB 1576|url=http://thewhorecast.com/podcast/episodes/episode-43/|website=The WhoreCast|accessdate=26 June 2014}}</ref>\nIn 2013, she was featured on CNN after organizing an Obamacare registration drive dubbed the \u201cHealthy Ho\u2019s Party.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fink|first1=Erica|title=Sex workers embrace Obamacare|url=http://money.cnn.com/2013/11/01/smallbusiness/sex-workers-obamacare/|website=CNN Money|accessdate=25 June 2014|date=November 2013}}</ref> The event, designed to encourage sex workers to enroll in newly established insurance exchanges, was declared a success, with nearly 40 attendees filing enrollment paperwork.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.thewhorecast.com}}\n* {{iafd name|id=SiouxsieQ|gender=female|name=Siouxsie Q}}\n* {{afdb name|63083|Siouxsie Q}}\n* [http://www.sfweekly.com/authors/siouxsie-q/ Siouxsie Q] at [[SF Weekly]]\n* [http://www.cosmopolitan.com/sex-love/a48141/porn-star-weddings/ \"4 Porn Stars Talk About How They Fell in Love\"]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Q, Siouxsie}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American columnists]]\n[[Category:American female erotic dancers]]\n[[Category:American erotic dancers]]\n[[Category:American pornographic film actresses]]\n[[Category:Pornographic film actors from California]]\n[[Category:Writers from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Women columnists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American journalist, pornographic actress and outspoken sex workers\u2019 rights activist}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Siouxsie Q\n| image         = Siouxsie Q 2019 by Glenn Francis.jpg\n| alt           = face of a woman with dark brown hair and brown eyes wearing a gold necklace looking at the camera \n| caption       = Siouxsie Q in Hollywood in October 2019\n| birth_name    = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date    = <!-- {{Birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people supply only the year with {{Birth year and age|YYYY}} unless the exact date is already widely published, as per [[WP:DOB]]. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. -->\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date) -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = \n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = \n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}'''Siouxsie Q''' is an American journalist, pornographic actress, and outspoken [[sex workers' rights|sex workers\u2019 rights]] activist who identifies herself as a [[feminist]] and [[sex worker]]. She is a podcaster, singer/songwriter and playwright as well as a widely read columnist with [[SF Weekly]] in San Francisco.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Levine|first1=Katie|title=Sex Nerd Sandra #136: Sex Work with Siouxsie Q plus Matt Kirshen|url=http://www.nerdist.com/pepisode/sex-nerd-sandra-136-sex-work-with-siouxsie-q-plus-matt-kirshen/|website=The Nerdist|accessdate=26 June 2014|date=2014-03-26}}</ref>\n\n== Personal ==\nSiouxsie Q is based in San Francisco and is married to fellow podcaster and journalist Jesse James. They have a [[Polyamory|polyamorous]] relationship.<ref>{{cite|last= Siouxsie Q|date= 2016|title= Truth, Justice and the American Whore|publisher= ThreeL Media|isbn= 0990557154}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAfter appearing on amateur sites Dare Ring and being a contributor to the sellyoursextape videos (Ashley & Dakota) In 2010, Siouxsie Q left her retail job and began dancing at [[Lusty Lady|The Lusty Lady Theater]], a unionized peep show in North Beach, San Francisco.<ref>{{cite web|title=SF Fringe Festival to Offer Sex-Worker Siouxsie Q's FISH-GIRL|url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/san-francisco/article/SF-Fringe-Festival-to-Offer-Sex-Worker-Siouxsie-Qs-FISH-GIRL-More-96-21-20130731?%3E-page2# |website=Broadway World|accessdate=26 June 2014}}</ref> Shortly after, she began her career as a sex worker while living in Inner Richmond, commuting to an apartment in East Bay to conduct business.\n\nInitially using the Internet primarily as a marketing tool, Siouxsie has stated that podcasts have \"really transformed how I do business.\"<ref>{{Cite news|last1=Carroll|first1=Rory|title=Sex and Silicon Valley: the veritable arms race of the dating app industry|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jun/22/sex-silicon-valley-veritable-arms-race-dating-apps|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=29 June 2014|date=2014-06-22}}</ref> By 2012, she had settled into her career and, at the urging of her boyfriend, began a regular, biweekly podcast as a way to speak out against California\u2019s Proposition 35, Measure B. Originally called, \u201cThis American Whore,\u201d the podcast\u2019s name was eventually changed to \u201cThe WhoreCast\u201d after a dispute with \"[[This American Life]],\" the public radio program.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|authorlink=Laurie Segall|last1=Segall|first1=Laurie|last2=Fink|first2=Erica|title=Silicon Valley's other entrepreneurs: Sex workers|url=http://money.cnn.com/2013/04/15/technology/silicon-valley-sex-workers/|website=CNN Money|accessdate=25 June 2014|date=2013-04-15}}</ref> After the passing of Proposition 35, the podcast was expanded to cover a broad range of topics such as transgender issues, sexuality, sex workers\u2019 rights, politics and pornography.\n\nIn 2014, she began writing a regular column for SF Weekly in which she discusses the topics of pornography, feminism, sexuality and the sex work industry.\n\nShe was jointly nominated for Best All-Girl Group Sex Scene at the 2015 [[AVN Award]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://avnawards.avn.com/pages/4 |title=2016 AVN Awards|work=AVN|accessdate=22 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Political views ==\nBy way of her podcast, \u201cThe WhoreCast,\u201d Siouxsie Q emerged as an outspoken opponent of [[California elections, November 2012|California\u2019s Proposition 35]], Measure B, a part of the \u201cCalifornians Against Sexual Exploitation Act.\u201d In her broadcasts, she stated that she considered the proposition \u201ca confusing piece of legislation\u201d that too broadly expanded the definition of \u201ctrafficking\u201d to include anyone who lived with or derived support from someone who is a prostitute.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Q|first1=Siouxsie|title=Confessions of an American Whore: Sex Work Holds a Mirror Up to S.F.'s Hidden Kinks and Communities|url=http://www.sfweekly.com/2014-01-29/news/siouxsie-q-sex-workers-lusty-lady-fetish/|website=SF Weekly|accessdate=25 June 2014}}</ref> In response, The WhoreCast was established as \u201ca vehicle to really humanize sex work\u201d and as a way to oppose Proposition 35.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\nShe also utilized the podcast to speak out against [[Measure B|Assembly Bill 1576]], a bill that would require condoms be worn in all adult films made in California. She described the bill as \u201cpart of a multipronged strategy [\u2026] to shut down the porn industry in California.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|last1=Q|first1=Siouxsie|title=The Rubber State: Porn Finds the Condom Bill Ill-Fitting|url=http://www.sfweekly.com/2014-05-28/culture/whore-next-door-condom-bill-porn/|website=SF Weekly|accessdate=25 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The WhoreCast: Stop AB 1576|url=http://thewhorecast.com/podcast/episodes/episode-43/|website=The WhoreCast|accessdate=26 June 2014}}</ref>\nIn 2013, she was featured on CNN after organizing an Obamacare registration drive dubbed the \u201cHealthy Ho\u2019s Party.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|last1=Fink|first1=Erica|title=Sex workers embrace Obamacare|url=http://money.cnn.com/2013/11/01/smallbusiness/sex-workers-obamacare/|website=CNN Money|accessdate=25 June 2014|date=November 2013}}</ref> The event, designed to encourage sex workers to enroll in newly established insurance exchanges, was declared a success, with nearly 40 attendees filing enrollment paperwork.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.thewhorecast.com}}\n* {{iafd name|id=SiouxsieQ|gender=female|name=Siouxsie Q}}\n* {{afdb name|63083|Siouxsie Q}}\n* [http://www.sfweekly.com/authors/siouxsie-q/ Siouxsie Q] at [[SF Weekly]]\n* [http://www.cosmopolitan.com/sex-love/a48141/porn-star-weddings/ \"4 Porn Stars Talk About How They Fell in Love\"]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Q, Siouxsie}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American columnists]]\n[[Category:American female erotic dancers]]\n[[Category:American erotic dancers]]\n[[Category:American pornographic film actresses]]\n[[Category:Pornographic film actors from California]]\n[[Category:Writers from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Women columnists]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siouxsie_Q"}
{"title_page": "Swenglish", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=May 2011}}\n\n'''Swenglish''' is a colloquial term referring to the [[English language]] heavily influenced by [[Swedish language|Swedish]] in terms of [[vocabulary]], [[grammar]], or [[pronunciation]].<ref>Lambert, James. 2018. A multitude of \u2018lishes\u2019: The nomenclature of hybridity. ''English World-wide'', 39(1): 1-33. DOI: 10.1075/eww.38.3.04lam</ref> \n\n== English heavily influenced by Swedish ==\n[[File:Knowledge English Sweden 2005.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Knowledge of English in Sweden as reported by Swedes, 2005.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://ec.europa.eu/public_opinion/archives/ebs/ebs_243_en.pdf | title=Europeans and their Languages | publisher=[[European Commission]] | work=Special Eurobarometer 243 / Wave 64.3 - TNS Opinion & Social | date=February 2006 | accessdate=May 3, 2011}} According to this [[Eurobarometer]] survey, 89% of respondents in Sweden indicated that they know English well enough to have a conversation (p. 152). Of these 35% had a very good knowledge of the language, 42% had a good knowledge and 23% had basic English skills (p. 156).</ref> Very good: 31%  Good: 37%  Basic: 21%  Not enough: 11%]]\nThe name ''Swenglish'' is a [[portmanteau|portmanteau term]] of the names of the two languages and is first recorded from 1938, making it one of the oldest names for a hybrid form of English.<ref>Lambert, James. 2018. A multitude of \u2018lishes\u2019: The nomenclature of hybridity. ''English World-wide'', 39(1): 14. DOI: 10.1075/eww.38.3.04lam</ref> Other colloquial [[portmanteau word]]s for Swenglish include (chronologically): ''Swinglish'' (from 1957), ''Swedlish'' (1995) and ''Sweglish'' (1996).<ref>Lambert, James. 2018. A multitude of \u2018lishes\u2019: The nomenclature of hybridity. ''English World-wide'', 39(1): 31. DOI: 10.1075/eww.38.3.04lam</ref>\n=== Pronunciation ===\nSwedish is characterised by a strong [[word stress]] and [[phrase]] [[prosody (linguistics)|prosody]] that differs from that of English.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\nThere are words that are similar in meaning and pronunciation, that have different stress patterns. For example, verbs that end with ''-era'' in Swedish are often French loanwords, where the French word ends with a stressed ''-er''. The Swedish word gets its stress point at the same place, but this is not true in English. A native Swedish speaker might mispronounce ''generate'' as {{IPA-endia|d\u0292\u025bn\u0259\u02c8\u0279e\u026at|}}  by following the pattern of the Swedish {{lang|sv|generera}} {{IPA-sv|j\u025bn\u025b\u02c8r\u011b\u02d0ra|}}.\n\nSwedish is a [[Pitch-accent language|pitch accent]] language.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Niemeyer|first=T\u00fcbingen|title=Phonology and Morphology of the Germanic Languages|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|year=1998|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref> Accent 1 is a low-high-low contour and accent 2 is an high-low-high-low contour, with the second peak in the second syllable.<ref name=\":0\" /> This can give Swenglish speakers a \"singing\" quality to their speech. Particularly when exaggerating their Swedish accent in English, speakers add an extra cadence to their words that most native English speakers lack.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PrzwpZfONXY|title=Alexander Skarsgard Swedish Accent on Jimmy Fallon|last=Skarsgard|first=Alex|date=|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=13 July 2012|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nSwedish lacks many common English [[phonemes]]. These are sometimes replaced by similar-sounding Swedish phonemes, or other English phonemes that are easier to pronounce. For example, when using the nearest Swedish vowels for the English words ''[[beer]]'' and ''[[bear]]'', a native Swedish speaker might pronounce both as {{IPA-sv|be\u02d0r|}}. In general, Swenglish will sound very articulated, due to Swedish vowels being more strongly articulated and not as often reduced to [[schwa]]s.\n\nSwedish also lacks some consonant phonemes common in English, such as voiceless dental fricative {{IPAslink|\u03b8}}, which is typically realized as labiodental {{IPAblink|f}} or a voiceless dental stop {{IPAblink|t\u032a}}, leading to ''[[3|three]]'' being pronounced as \"free\" or \"[[tree]]\". Other missing consonants include voiced dental fricative {{IPAslink|\u00f0}}, which is typically realized as a voiced dental stop {{IPAblink|d\u032a}}), voiced alveolar fricative {{IPAslink|z}}, which is typically realized voicelessly {{IPAblink|s}} and voiced palato-alveolar fricative {{IPAslink|d\u0292}}, which is realized voicelessly {{IPAblink|t\u0283}}, somewhat more back {{IPAblink|\u0288\u0282}}, or as a voiced palatal approximant {{IPAblink|j}} or fricative {{IPAblink|\u029d}}.\n\nThere are examples of Swenglish being used in Sweden as a means of [[brand management]]. The Swedish telecommunications company [[Tele2]] since 2008 has aired commercials with a black sheep called ''Frank''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.resume.se/nyheter/artiklar/2008/11/05/faraktigt-tele2/ |title=F\u00e5raktigt, Tele2 |publisher=resume.se |language=Swedish |date=5 November 2008 |accessdate=2 August 2016}}</ref> The pun of the commercials is based on the English word ''cheap'', which usually is pronounced as \"sheep\" by Swedes\u2014hence ''Frank''.\n\n=== Vocabulary and grammar ===\nAs with most non-native speech, native Swedish speakers may pick the wrong word when speaking English based on what sounds right in their own language. While Swedish and English share many words, both from their Germanic origins, and from later French and Latin influence, there are several Swedish-English [[false friends]], such as ''nacke'' meaning \u2019nape, back of the neck\u2019 (similar to English \"neck\"), and ''eventuellt'' meaning \u2019possibly\u2019 (similar to \"eventually\"). Some [[loanword]]s have a more specific meaning in Swedish than the original English, such as ''keyboard'' meaning only \u2019[[electronic keyboard]], [[synthesizer]]\u2019. Compare the list of [[:sv:Lista \u00f6ver falska v\u00e4nner mellan svenska och engelska|Swedish-English false friends on Swedish Wikipedia]].\n\nMany Swedish compounds and expressions translate directly into English, but many others do not, even if the translations can be understood. For instance, the Swedish ''ta med'' means \u2019bring\u2019, but is often translated as the literal \"take with\".\n\n===Controversies===\nIn June 2010, [[BP]]'s Swedish chairman [[Carl-Henric Svanberg]] famously caused a PR uproar after the [[Deepwater Horizon oil spill]] by referring to the [[common people]] as \"the small people\", drawing upon the Swedish phrase ''den lilla m\u00e4nniskan''.\n\nIn December 2019, climate activist [[Greta Thunberg]] was criticised by some right-wing commentators after saying said politicians should be put \"against the wall\", a term which in English can be interpreted as [[execution by firing squad]]. She later apologised, saying \"...that's Swenglish: \"att st\u00e4lla n\u00e5gon mot v\u00e4ggen\" (to put someone against the wall) means to hold someone accountable\", and that she is against violence.<ref>https://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/474608-greta-thunberg-apologizes-after-saying-politicians-should-be</ref>\n\n=== ''Svengelska'' ===\nThe [[Swedish language]] term ''svengelska'' refers not to Swenglish, but to spoken or written Swedish filled with an inordinate amount of English syntax and words, with the latter sometimes respelled according to the norms of Swedish phonetics, or [[calque]]d into Swedish.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Sweden|Languages}}\n*[[Non-native pronunciations of English]]\n*[[Svorsk]]\n*[[Spr\u00e5kf\u00f6rsvaret]]\n*[[Swedish Chef]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book | last = Moon | first = Colin | title = Sweden - More Secret Files: Swedish, Swenglish and What they Really Mean | publisher = Today Press | location = Uppsala | year = 2002 | isbn = 978-91-974192-1-5 }}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.thelocal.se/20120906/43046 The Local: Swenglish: the definitive guide and top ten]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070225023929/http://www.awaywithwords.se/swenglish.htm Test Your Swenglish]. Lists some common mistakes of Swedish speakers of English.\n\n{{Swedish language}}\n{{Interlanguage varieties}}\n\n[[Category:Macaronic forms of English]]\n[[Category:Swedish language|English]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=May 2011}}\n\n'''Swenglish''' is a colloquial term referring to the [[English language]] heavily influenced by [[Swedish language|Swedish]] in terms of [[vocabulary]], [[grammar]], or [[pronunciation]].<ref>Lambert, James. 2018. A multitude of \u2018lishes\u2019: The nomenclature of hybridity. ''English World-wide'', 39(1): 1-33. DOI: 10.1075/eww.38.3.04lam</ref> \n\n== English heavily influenced by Swedish ==\n[[File:Knowledge English Sweden 2005.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Knowledge of English in Sweden as reported by Swedes, 2005.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://ec.europa.eu/public_opinion/archives/ebs/ebs_243_en.pdf | title=Europeans and their Languages | publisher=[[European Commission]] | work=Special Eurobarometer 243 / Wave 64.3 - TNS Opinion & Social | date=February 2006 | accessdate=May 3, 2011}} According to this [[Eurobarometer]] survey, 89% of respondents in Sweden indicated that they know English well enough to have a conversation (p. 152). Of these 35% had a very good knowledge of the language, 42% had a good knowledge and 23% had basic English skills (p. 156).</ref> Very good: 31%  Good: 37%  Basic: 21%  Not enough: 11%]]\nThe name ''Swenglish'' is a [[portmanteau|portmanteau term]] of the names of the two languages and is first recorded from 1938, making it one of the oldest names for a hybrid form of English.<ref>Lambert, James. 2018. A multitude of \u2018lishes\u2019: The nomenclature of hybridity. ''English World-wide'', 39(1): 14. DOI: 10.1075/eww.38.3.04lam</ref> Other colloquial [[port